xt{OOD}}caligraphic\\_D start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_M , OOD end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT are used at any stage for training the regression model.\n\n## 4 Experiments\n\nIn this section, we present the experimental setup to evaluate our ASR metrics approximation tool. We describe the datasets, models, and regression pipeline used in our experiments, highlighting the diversity of ASR systems and testing conditions.\n\n### 4.1 Datasets\n\nTo evaluate the robustness and generalizability of our ASR metrics approximation tool, we use datasets sourced from multiple distributions, divided into two types: Standard Benchmark and Wild Challenge datasets. Below we describe the datasets and provide additional details in Appendix [A.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS2 \"A.2 Datasets ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") Table [3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.T3 \"Table 3 ‣ A.2.2 Wild Challenge Set ‣ A.2 Datasets ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\nStandard Benchmark Datasets. We include widely used datasets representing diverse domains and acoustic conditions. LibriSpeech Panayotov et al. ([2015](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib36)) provides 1,000 hours of English read audiobooks, covering both clean and noisy conditions. TED-LIUM Rousseau et al. ([2014](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib47)) consists of TED talks from 2,000 speakers. GigaSpeech Chen et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib9)) spans audiobooks, podcasts, and YouTube, incorporating both read and spontaneous speech. SPGISpeech Technologies ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib55)) features 5,000 hours of earnings calls with a focus on orthographic accuracy. Common Voice Ardila et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib4)) is a multilingual, crowdsourced corpus with diverse accents. Earnings22 Rio et al. ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib46)) provides 119 hours of accented, real-world earnings calls. Additional datasets include AMI (IHM) Carletta et al. ([2005](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib8)), with 100 hours of English meeting recordings from non-native speakers, and People’s Speech Galvez et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib16)), emphasizing inclusivity and linguistic diversity. SLUE-VoXCeleb Shon et al. ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib52)) contains conversational voice snippets, capturing diverse speaking styles and emotions.\n\nWild Datasets. The wild set focuses on real-world variability and challenging scenarios. Primock57 Papadopoulos Korfiatis et al. ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib37)) includes telemedicine consultations with diverse accents, ages, and scenarios, recorded by clinicians and actors. VoxPopuli Accented Wang et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib60)) contains multilingual speeches from European Parliament recordings, rich in named entities. ATCOsim Jan van Doorn ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib23)) features 10 hours of non-native English speech from air traffic control simulations with clean utterance-level transcriptions. Additionally, we include a noisy subset of LibriSpeech Panayotov et al. ([2015](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib36)), which reflects challenging real-world conditions.\n\n### 4.2 Models\n\nWe evaluate our approximation framework for a range of state-of-the-art ASR models, put into three categories based on their architecture and functionality. Below we describe the datasets and provide additional details in Appendix [A.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS2 \"A.2 Datasets ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") and in Table [4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.T4 \"Table 4 ‣ A.3 Models ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\nEncoder-Decoder Models.\nWe include multiple encoder-decoder families of models capable of performing ASR tasks in a zero-shot setting. More specifically, we include whisper Radford et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib42)) and distil-whisper Gandhi et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib17)) models which perform really well across diverse testing settings. We also include seamless  Communication et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib11)); Seamless Communication et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib49)); Barrault et al. ([2025](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib7)), SpeechT5 Ao et al. ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib3)) which are unified encoder-decoder framework for tasks such as ASR, speech synthesis, translation, and voice conversion. MMS Pratap et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib39)) supports hundreds of languages and excels in resource-constrained scenarios. Moonshine (2) Jeffries et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib24)), a lightweight and efficient model, is designed for edge deployments with strong performance.\n\nNeMo-ASR Models.\nWe use multiple models from the NeMo-ASR Gulati et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib18)); Variani et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib56)); Noroozi et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib34)); Tang et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib54)); [Harper et al.](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib20)  toolkit by NVIDIA. We include models such as Canary and Parakeet, which use highly efficient speech encoders like Fast-Conformer Rekesh et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib45)). In addition to that, we use models based on various encoders, and decoders (CTC, RNN-T, TDT, Conformer-CTC Guo et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib19)). In our work, we evaluate 11 models from the NeMo-ASR toolkit.\n\nEncoder-Only and Decoder-Only Models.\nWe include self-supervised encoder-only models and their derivatives, as well as decoder-only models like SpeechLLM. Specifically, we use Wav2Vec2 Schneider et al. ([2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib48)); Baevski et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib6)), HuBERT Hsu et al. ([2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib21)), and Data2Vec Baevski et al. ([2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib5)). Additionally, we include speech language models like SpeechLLM [Rajaa and Tushar](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib44) , which combines speech embeddings with language models to predict metadata such as speaker attributes, emotions, and accents, offering robust multimodal capabilities.\n\n### 4.3 Experimental Setup\n\nWe evaluate all models listed in Section [4.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S4.SS2 \"4.2 Models ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") on 1000100010001000 examples sampled randomly from the t⁢e⁢s⁢t𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡testitalic\\_t italic\\_e italic\\_s italic\\_t split of each dataset, as described in Section [4.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S4.SS1 \"4.1 Datasets ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"). Since all models are trained at a 16 kHz sampling rate, we (re)sample the speech accordingly. For ASR, we use greedy decoding and all other parameters are default unless otherwise specified. We apply basic text post-processing 111<https://bit.ly/enormwhisper> before computing ASR metrics. We obtain all models from Huggingface Hub 222<https://huggingface.co/models> and implement the ASR pipeline using the Transformers Wolf et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib62)) library.\n\nFor multimodal embeddings, we use SONAR Duquenne et al. ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib14)), a 1024-dimensional sentence-level multilingual embedding model. Specifically, we utilize text\\_sonar\\_basic\\_encoder for text encoding and speech\\_sonar\\_basic\\_encoder for speech encoding. These encoders provide unified representations.\n\nThe regression framework uses a stacking ensemble with base regressors and a final estimator. Hyperparameter tuning is performed with RandomizedSearchCV to minimize MAE. The model is trained on 9 benchmark datasets and evaluated on the remaining benchmark dataset and four in-the-wild datasets. This process is repeated for all 10 benchmark datasets. Additional details of the regression pipeline are provided in Section [3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3 \"3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") and low-level details in Appendix [A.4.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS4.SSS1 \"A.4.1 Regression Pipeline. ‣ A.4 Experiments ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\nWe conduct ASR experiments on a single A100/H100 GPU, while the regression model training runs on CPUs. Although ASR time and memory consumption depend on the model size, embedding extraction for 1000100010001000 audio-text pairs takes approximately one minute on a single consumer-grade GPU without parallelization or additional efficiency measures. Appendix [A.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS4 \"A.4 Experiments ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") provides further experimental setup details.\n\nBaselines.\nRecent studies directly aligned with our approach are limited. For instance, eWER Ali and Renals ([2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib1)) and eWER2 Ali and Renals ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib2)) estimate error rates based on the input signal, which differs from our approach. In contrast, we incorporate the model’s output transcript into the error rate approximation function. The most closely related recent works are WERBERT Sheshadri et al. ([2021a](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib50)) and eWER3 Chowdhury and Ali ([2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib10)), which share a similar pipeline. Both use encoders for text, speech, and other data, followed by a regression model trained in an end-to-end setting. Since eWER3 is the more recent of the two, we use it as our baseline. In eWER3, the speech encoder is *wav2vec2* Baevski et al. ([2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib6)), and the text encoder is *roberta-base* Liu et al. ([2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#bib.bib32)), with a regression model trained on top while both encoders remain frozen. Given the unavailability of public code or pretrained models for evaluation, we implement eWER3 with some modifications to ensure a fair comparison. Specifically, we extract features from both encoders and apply PCA for dimensionality reduction on each modality before training our regression pipeline. For both speech and text, we experiment with 32 and 64 PCA components (referred to as n⁢c𝑛𝑐ncitalic\\_n italic\\_c in Table [5.3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S5.SS3 \"5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\")).\n\n## 5 Results\n\nWe conduct experiments using two dataset categories: standard benchmarks and in-the-wild, as described in Section [4.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S4.SS1 \"4.1 Datasets ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"). For each ASR model, a leave-one-out strategy is used, training the regression model on 9 benchmark datasets and testing it on the remaining benchmark dataset and all four in-the-wild datasets to ensure comprehensive evaluation exclusively on out-of-domain data. Additionally, in-domain testing is included in ablation studies, as detailed in Section [5.3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S5.SS3 \"5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"). The regression model is trained to predict absolute error counts (word and character levels), which are normalized by the reference length to compute approximate error rates (a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R and a⁢C⁢E⁢R𝑎𝐶𝐸𝑅aCERitalic\\_a italic\\_C italic\\_E italic\\_R). We also train regression models to directly predict WER and CER.\n\n### 5.1 Evaluation on In-the-Wild Datasets\n\nThe wild datasets provide a realistic testbed for evaluating the regression model’s ability to approximate error rates under real-world conditions. The results are presented in Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S5.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 5.1 Evaluation on In-the-Wild Datasets ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"). High-performing models, like canary-1b, demonstrate strong agreement between predicted and actual error rates. For example, on VP\\_Accented, canary-1b achieves a WER of 23.2%percent23.223.2\\%23.2 % and an a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R of 12.1%percent12.112.1\\%12.1 %, with a minimal difference of 1.1%percent1.11.1\\%1.1 %. On Primock57, a clinical consultation dataset, the model shows robustness with a WER of 16.2%percent16.216.2\\%16.2 % and an a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R of 13.4%percent13.413.4\\%13.4 %, highlighting its effective generalization across diverse and domain-specific contexts.\n\nFor models like data2vec-audio-large-960h our approximation is pretty close to actual error rates with difference consistently under 2%percent22\\%2 % on various datasets. For example, on LibriSpeech-test-noise, the model’s actual WER is 7.2%percent7.27.2\\%7.2 % while the approximated a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R is 8.6%percent8.68.6\\%8.6 %, showcasing its reliability in noisy conditions. Even on acoustically complex datasets like ATCOsim, where the WER is 44.0%percent44.044.0\\%44.0 % and the a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R is 51.1%percent51.151.1\\%51.1 %, the model exhibits a reasonable alignment between approximated and actual error rates.\n\nIn contrast, models with high actual error rates, such as mms-1b-fl102, show slightly larger deviations, particularly on datasets with challenging conditions. For instance, on ATCOsim, the WER is 93.4%percent93.493.4\\%93.4 % and the a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R is 99.0%percent99.099.0\\%99.0 %, resulting in a significant deviation of 5.6%percent5.65.6\\%5.6 %, the highest observed across all in-the-wild datasets. Similarly, on Primock57, where the WER is 70.2%percent70.270.2\\%70.2 % and the a⁢W⁢E⁢R𝑎𝑊𝐸𝑅aWERitalic\\_a italic\\_W italic\\_E italic\\_R is 67.8%percent67.867.8\\%67.8 %, the approximation also struggles to align due to the inherently high error rates. This highlights that extreme error cases often correspond to semantically nonsensical outputs, where the distinction between high and extremely high error rates becomes less relevant.\n\n| Model | LS\\_Noise | Primock57 | ATCOsim | VP\\_Acc |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| w2v2-ls | 8.8/10.2 | 32.8/35.6 | 43.0/49.5 | 20.4/26.4 |\n| can-1b | 4.1/6.4 | 16.2/13.4 | 30.4/35.5 | 23.2/12.1 |\n| d2v-base | 14.9/16.4 | 39.6/4