-l | 6.2/8.1 | 18.8/13.9 | 65.3/66.9 | 18.7/15.9 |\n| whisper-l-v2 | 5.4/6.6 | 19.0/13.1 | 64.8/74.8 | 20.0/18.1 |\n| whisper-l-v3 | 4.6/5.9 | 18.7/12.0 | 64.7/73.9 | 19.2/18.1 |\n| whisper-l-v3-t | 4.9/6.0 | 18.5/12.3 | 66.0/72.5 | 24.3/23.2 |\n| whisper-m.en | 6.5/7.9 | 19.5/14.0 | 66.2/73.8 | 27.6/26.4 |\n| whisper-s.en | 8.2/9.7 | 20.0/15.1 | 67.1/73.8 | 17.3/17.5 |\n| whisper-tiny | 18.5/20.7 | 30.0/26.6 | 97.6/102.5 | 29.8/33.2 |\n\n### 5.2 Evaluation on Benchmark Datasets\n\nWe summarize results on 10 standard benchmark datasets in Appendix [A.5](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS5 \"A.5 Results ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") Tables [8](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.T8 \"Table 8 ‣ A.5 Results ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") and [9](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.T9 \"Table 9 ‣ A.5 Results ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"). Each table reports actual WER/CER alongside the approximated WER/CER (denoted by aWER/aCER).\n\n![Refer to caption](x2.png)\n\nOverall, models such as parakeet-tdt-1.1b and whisper-large-v3 show relatively small differences between WER and aWER, indicating reliable approximations. For instance, the actual WER for whisper-large-v3 on AMI\\_IHM is 19.0% compared to aWER 17.1%, 1.9% gap. Conversely, some challenging datasets (e.g., CV11 and Earnings22) reveal larger discrepancies for specific models, particularly those with higher overall error rates. For example, mms-1b-fl102 exhibits a wide WER/aWER gap on Earnings22, suggesting difficulty handling accented or domain-specific speech.\n\nIn general, high-performing ASR models demonstrate small WER–aWER gaps, indicating that it’s easy to approximate when error rates are low. However, models with higher WERs or faced with more acoustically or linguistically challenging test sets tend to show wider divergences. Despite these variations, most results remain within a reasonable margin, highlighting the robustness of our approximation model on diverse out-of-distribution data.\n\nThese results underscore the critical role of model quality in achieving reliable approximations. The approximation framework remains effective for high-performing models, while deviations tend to increase in cases of semantically divergent or poorly structured outputs, reflecting the inherent challenges in approximating errors for low-performing systems.\n\n### 5.3 Ablation\n\nWe conduct ablation experiments to evaluate the robustness of the approximation model and the contributions of its individual components. Using the evaluation setup outlined in Section [3.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3.SS4 \"3.4 Evaluation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), we select data2vec-audio-base-960h as the source model (S𝑆Sitalic\\_S) and wav2vec2-base-960h as the target model (T𝑇Titalic\\_T). The results are summarized in Table [5.3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S5.SS3 \"5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), where IID results correspond to Case-I [3.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3.SS4.SSS0.Px1 \"Case 1: IID Evaluation (Source 𝑆) ‣ 3.4 Evaluation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), and D𝐷Ditalic\\_D, M𝑀Mitalic\\_M, and D+M𝐷𝑀D+Mitalic\\_D + italic\\_M under OOD represent Case II [3.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3.SS4.SSS0.Px2 \"Case 2: IID Evaluation (Target 𝑇) ‣ 3.4 Evaluation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), Case-III [3.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3.SS4.SSS0.Px3 \"Case 3: OOD Evaluation (Source 𝑆) ‣ 3.4 Evaluation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), and Case-IV [3.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S3.SS4.SSS0.Px4 \"Case 4: OOD Evaluation (Target 𝑇) ‣ 3.4 Evaluation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\"), respectively. The reference model’s r𝑟ritalic\\_r value represents the average WER across all datasets. We include reference models with varying r𝑟ritalic\\_r values, such as whisper-large-v3 (r=17.8𝑟17.8r=17.8italic\\_r = 17.8), whisper-medium.en (r=20.1𝑟20.1r=20.1italic\\_r = 20.1), whisper-tiny (r=33.4𝑟33.4r=33.4italic\\_r = 33.4), and mms-1b-fl102 (r=51.0𝑟51.0r=51.0italic\\_r = 51.0).\n\nThe results in Table [5.3](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#S5.SS3 \"5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\") demonstrate the importance of proxy references in improving the regression model’s performance. Training without proxy references (w/o PR) significantly increases the mean absolute error (MAE) across all conditions. For instance, the IID MAE increases from 1.031.031.031.03 (Base) to 3.133.133.133.13, and the OOD D+M𝐷𝑀D+Mitalic\\_D + italic\\_M MAE rises from 1.071.071.071.07 (Base) to 3.333.333.333.33, highlighting the essential role of proxy references in approximation.\n\nIncreasing the number of high-quality proxy references (MPR) further reduces errors. Under IID conditions, the MAE decreases from 1.001.001.001.00 with n=2𝑛2n=2italic\\_n = 2 to 0.930.930.930.93 with n=5𝑛5n=5italic\\_n = 5. Similarly, in OOD D+M𝐷𝑀D+Mitalic\\_D + italic\\_M, the error drops from 1.061.061.061.06 (MPR, n=2𝑛2n=2italic\\_n = 2) to 0.950.950.950.95 (MPR, n=5𝑛5n=5italic\\_n = 5), demonstrating that multiple high-quality references enhance model robustness.\n\n|  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Method | IID | OOD | | |\n| D | M | D +